1. Direct the City Accountant to use accrual basis of accounting in income recognizing the income earned from the ACDC by timely recording in the books all outstanding PhilHealth claims;
2. Direct the City Accountant to effect the necessary adjusting journal entries to reflect the correct income and outstanding PhilHealth claims of the ACDC; and
3. Direct the Medical Records Officer of ACDC to regularly provide the City Accountant a copy of the list of outstanding PhilHealth claims for proper recording.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal General Services Officer (GSO) to:
a. Furnish the Office of the Auditor with a copy of PO, irrespective of amount and each of every supporting document, within five working days from the issuance thereof, in compliance with Item 3.2.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001;
b. Notify the Office of the Auditor of the time and date of every scheduled delivery of procured items within 24 hours from its acceptance, in compliance with Item A(2) of COA Circular No. 96-010;
c. Complete the lacking information from the noted POs to avoid the issuance of Notice of Suspension; and
d. Adhere with Item B of COA Circular No. 96-010 on the preparation of PO complete with all the necessary information pertaining to the procurement to ensure that the supplier will deliver the items in accordance with the terms and conditions of the contract.

We recommended that Management:
Adhere to the general process of handling and accounting for inventories and supplies and materials;
Advise the GSO to maintain stock cards for each category of supplies instead of per PO;
Advise the GSO to prepare the SSMI on a weekly basis and forward the same to the Accounting Unit to serve as basis in the preparation of JEV and recording of issuances;
Advise the Accounting Unit to maintain the perpetual inventory records comprising of SLC for each commodity/stock; and
Instruct the Inventory Committee to regularly conduct actual physical count of inventory and reconcile the same with the records of the City Accountant and the GSO.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to:
Conduct a complete physical inventory of all properties owned by the City Government and render report not later than January 31 of the ensuing year;
Reconcile and investigate the noted deficiencies against the property and accounting records;
Identify all unserviceable properties and undertake the necessary procedures to dispose them; and
Facilitate the completion of the one-time cleansing of PPE to arrive at an accurate and reliable amount of PPE accounts.
Instruct the City Accountant to prepare and maintain Real Property Ledger Cards for Land account;
Direct the City GSO to coordinate with the City Accountant to conduct regular monitoring and updating of property and accounting records for easy reconciliation.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the City Assessor to follow-up with the CENRO-DENR on the status of the titling of the 15 parcels of land. This will facilitate the approval and the issuance of TCT in the name of the LGU, as well as the issuance of clearance of the 12 parcels of land with the Philippine Reclamation Authority;
Instruct the City Assessor to facilitate the transfer and registration of ownership with the LRA for the remaining parcels of land to establish absolute ownership and protect the interest of the City Government;
Require the City Assessor to coordinate with the City Accountant to reconcile their records regarding the Land account; and
Instruct the City Budget Officer to allocate funds intended for the survey and titling of parcels of land.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of local road networks and submit the RPCLRN to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of the ensuing year;
Instruct the GSO to periodically render a Report on Local Road Network and furnish copies to the concerned offices;
Instruct the City Engineer to provide the City Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
Require the GSO and the City Accountant to prepare and maintain property cards and ledger cards, respectively;
Instruct the City Accountant to disclose the Road Network System in the Notes to the Financial Statement in conformity with the prescribed format; and
Ensure coordination among LGU offices represented by the City Accountant, GSO and City Engineer to properly implement the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Roads Asset Management System.

We recommended that Management:

Require the City Treasurer, in coordination with the City Tourism Officer and Market and Cemetery Officer, to submit to the City Accountant the report/list of delinquent stall rentals for CY 2022;

submit monthly statement of accounts of all stall owners to the City Accountant for proper recording in the books;

reconcile their records to determine the delinquent stall rentals as of December 31, 2022 and submit the report to the City Accountant for further recording; and

Require the City Accountant, upon receipt of the report/list of delinquent stall rentals, to draw a journal entry to record the delinquent stall rentals for CY 2022 totaling ₱97,727.92.

We recommended that Management:
Require the City Engineer to provide the City Accountant copies of Certificate of Completion on said infrastructure projects;
Require the City Accountant to draw a JEV to reclassify the costs of completed projects in the amount of ₱79,180,684.38 to the appropriate asset accounts based on Certificates of Completion and to provide the necessary depreciation attributed to the completed projects.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. require the Inventory Committee to submit the RPCLRN;
b. instruct the LRNPCs and Municipal General Services Officer (GSO) to maintain LRNPC and prepare a RLRN;
c. request the Municipal Engineer to provide the description and cost segregation of road components; and
d. direct the Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain the LRNLC and reconcile the same with the results of physical inventory.

Require all Punong Barangays to intensify the conduct of on-site house-to-house campaigns for waste segregation, to appropriately dispose of collected biodegradable and compostable materials, and to find best uses and appropriate actions concerning the recyclable materials;

Require the Solid Waste Management Board (SWMB) to make representation with the DENR on the status of their evaluation of the reviewed SWMP and to consistently update such plan as required by law;

Require the SWMB to provide all personnel dealing with collection of solid waste with personal protective equipment and paraphernalia; and



Require the SWMB to discourage entry of scavengers and unauthorized personnel to the landfill cells to avoid exposure from hazardous materials.

We recommended that management take the following course of action:
1. City General Services Office
1.a Prioritize the conduct of a periodic physical count of its inventories and report the same in the prescribed Report of Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) and cause its submission to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year in accordance with Section 124 of NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1. Where necessary, create an inventory committee to expedite such inventory taking;
1.b Consolidate weekly the RIS for which supplies and materials were issued using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued. The SSMI together with the original copy of the RIS shall be submitted to the Chief Accountant;
1.c Maintain an updated Stock cards for each specific type of Inventories to facilitate verification and reconciliation with accounting records.
2. City Accounting Office
2.a Strictly apply the perpetual inventory method in recording inventory purchases and outflow of the same pursuant to Section 114 of NGAS for Local Government Units, Volume 1. In addition detailed inventory records are maintained for each inventory item;
2.b Prepare JEV on the basis of SSMI and designate an accounting personnel with sense of responsibility to maintain dutifully an updated Supplies Ledger Card for each specific type of Inventories to facilitate verification and reconciliation with property cards.

